-- 
BG, Deutsche Bank, EnBW, E.ON, Renault: European Equity Preview

-- B y   C e c i l e   V a n n u c c i
-- 
2011-03-15T04:00:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-14/bg-deutsche-bank-enbw-e-on-henderson-renault-europe-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index fell 1.1 percent to 272.51. The
Stoxx 50 Index declined 1.1 percent to 2,566.81. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, dropped 1.1
percent to 2,852.11.    BG Group Plc (BG/)  : The U.K.’s third-largest natural-gas
producer said it plans to bid for the rights to explore for oil
in upcoming auctions in  Brazil , which won’t include blocks in
the so-called pre-salt area. The shares climbed 3.7 percent to
1,514 pence.    Close Brothers Group Plc (CBG)  : The British investment
bank founded in 1878 is scheduled to report first-half net
income. The stock declined 0.2 percent to 860.5 pence.    Deutsche Bank AG (DBK)  :  Germany ’s largest lender sold
$100 million in claims on bankrupt Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc.
to Dolostone LLC of  New York , according to a bankruptcy court
filing. The shares declined 0.3 percent to 42.63 euros.    EnBW Energie Baden-Wuerttemberg AG (EBK)  : Stefan Mappus,
the prime minister of the German state of Baden-Wuerttemberg,
said the Neckarwestheim I nuclear reactor operated by EnBW will
be shut down “as soon as possible.” The shares rose less than
0.1 percent to 41.32 euros.    E.ON AG (EOAN)   and  RWE AG (RWE)  : Markus Soeder, the
environment minister in the German state of Bavaria, wants to
shut E.ON’s Isar 1 nuclear reactor,  Deutsche Presse-Agentur 
reported, without saying where it obtained the information.  Separately, the Christian Democratic Union party of German  Chancellor Angela Merkel  expects the Neckarwestheim I, the
Biblis A and the Isar I nuclear reactors to be closed down, at
least temporarily, Suedwestrundfunk reported, citing Peter
Altmaier, a parliament member of the CDU.  Shares of E.ON, Germany’s largest utility, declined 5.3
percent to 21.87 euros. RWE, which operates the Biblis A
reactor, dropped 4.8 percent to 45.64 euros.    G4S Plc (GFS)  : The world’s largest security company may
report full-year net income of 225.8 million pounds ($316
million) according to the average of eight estimates compiled by
Bloomberg. The shares fell 1.9 percent to 256.9 pence.    Henderson Group Plc (HGG)  : Henderson U.K. Finance Plc
plans to issue five-year bonds in exchange for 175 million
pounds of outstanding 6.5 percent notes due 2012, the company
said in a Regulatory News Service statement. The new securities
will be priced to yield at least 445 basis points more than 2016
U.K. Gilts, Henderson said. The stock declined 0.3 percent to
160.5 pence.    Nyrstar (NYR)  NV: The world’s biggest producer of
refined zinc is scheduled to report the take-up of its 490.1
million-euro rights offering and will sell the unexercised
subscription rights in a so-called scrip placement during
trading hours. Nyrstar advanced 0.7 percent to 10.03 euros.    Renault SA (RNO)  : The carmaker proposed to reinstate
three employees wrongfully accused of spying and said Chief
Executive Officer  Carlos Ghosn  and Chief Operating Officer
Patrick Pelata will give up their 2010 Bonus and 2011 stock
options. The shares retreated 6.3 percent to 38.18 euros.    Scor SE (SCR)  :  France ’s largest reinsurer estimated its
property and casualty business will have total net losses below
185 million euros from the earthquake in  Japan  last week. The
stock fell 3.4 percent to 18.60 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Cecile Vannucci in New York at 
 cvannucci1@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
